    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-12-02T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-12-02T05:00:00-05:00" n="706"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d706">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/13301: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hankow</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Josselyn</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-12-02T18:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 2, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 11 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>63. My November 30, 4 p.m. Ho Lung and Hsiao reported to be moving rapidly
                    westward from the Yiyang–Sinhwa area towards the Kweichow border which they may
                    already have crossed. American Catholic Mission in Chihkiang telegraphed
                    yesterday that Hsiao was moving by way of Hurigkiang, Ho Lung by way of
                    Chihkiang and a third body by way of Mayang. Most of the troops in the province
                    are in the northwest. Some nervousness in Changsha where there are practically
                    no troops and numerous missionaries have moved there from Yiyang, Ningsiang and
                    Poaking. Reenforcements reported on their way from Kiangsi and the Hunan troops
                    are following the Communists. The Standard Vacuum Oil Company are holding their
                    steamer <hi rend="italic">Meishan</hi> at Changsha pending developments.</p>
                <pb facs="0811" n="699" xml:id="pg_699"/>
                <p>2. Hunan Provincial Government telegraphed me November 30 that it ordered the
                    military units at the front in conjunction with the magistrates to protect
                    missionaries in Chihkiang and other districts. Repeated to Department, Peiping,
                    Nanking, Canton.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Josselyn</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
